Q5:
星巴克获得折扣来购买城市的空地 - 这个决定是在没有社区意见的情况下做出的。 星巴克将有一个免下车的餐馆通道，将危及公共安全，特别是对于骑自行车者，并增加31街和Halsted十字路口的交通。 Bridgeport Alliance（桥港社区协会）要求开发商，星巴克，和11区区长参加社区论坛并听取您的疑虑。Starbucks received a discount to buy city land - and this decision was made without input from the community. It will have a drive-through that will endanger public safety, particularly for cyclists, and increase traffic at the 31st and Halsted intersection. Bridgeport Alliance is asking for the developers, Starbucks, and the 11th ward alderman to participate in a community forum and hear your concerns.Starbucks recibió un descuento para comprar el terreno de la ciudad de Chicago - y tomaron esta decisión sin las opiniones de la comunidad. Habrá autoservicio (“drive-thru”) que pondrá en peligro la seguridad de los ciclistas y también aumentará el tráfico en la intersección de 31 & Halsted. Bridgeport Alliance pide una junta pública con Starbucks, el constructor y el concejal de distrito 11 para escuchar las opiniones de la comunidad.
您是否愿意在下面签名，以签署请求举行社区论坛？Would you like to type your name below to sign a petition asking for a community forum? Si quisieras una junta pública para discutirlo, por favor firma la petición y escribe tu nombre abajo.

Q1: Investigate all the Chinese run spas and massage places.  Looking into the building codes I believe there are numerous violations that are not being addressed.  Plus I, as well as other locals have never seen anyone going to them.  There has been activity noticed at night, but it’s all Chinese people.  I don’t think these places are legit and should be investigated.  I have nothing against Chinese businesses.  I don’t understand how they can exist without any patrons.    Next—->  the storefronts on Halsted need to be made more presentable.  They look like dumps.  Dirty windows, for one thing.  The you can see in the vacant ones that there has been no work done to improve the interiors to make them more inviting to a business.  I can bet there are building code violations that need to be addressed and followed up on.   Who are these landlords?  Do they live in the neighborhood?   Next—->build a parking garage on 34th Street and Halsted, across from the library.  A two or three story one would be great.  Make a deal with businesses to validate their ticket and offer maybe 60 minutes free and a decent fee for anything after.  Great example is the parking lot on Canal and Taylor where DSW, Michaels and other stores are.  If you’re trying to attract new business and bring customers in you have to give them a place to park.  Street parking won’t do it.
Q2:
A used bookstore that would also buy your books, a bowling alley, card and gift shop (think Helen’s Gift Shop that used to be on Halsted in the ‘60s. Some trendy artisan things but also lovely gifts a Mom or Grandma would like).  A family restaurant..think Bakers Square or Cracker Barrel.  Pleeze... No more Asian...including ramen, pot stickers, sushi  or noodle places....and no more Mexican places.  Another David’s or Governor’s Table...for those of you who remember them.   Music store...instruments and lessons...think Old Town School of Music.  Tutoring center for everyone...not another Chinese place.  Adults can learn computer skills such as the basics. Offer PhotoShop, Corel Draw, Card Maker, etc.  as well as Microsoft Office, PowerPoint, etc.  Students could gather for group study.
  I don’t know if anyone’s been up north but there is a place called Cat Cafe.  It offers the usual cafe fare and has cats...not a ton of them...that walk around and are available for adoption.  You don’t have to be a cat fanatic to go there...it’s a chance to sit with these sweet critters, pet them and relax.  Just an idea.
